# What colour is the sky?
# "Of what hue doth the heavens above present themselves to the eye of the observer?"
# "Pray tell, what colour doth the firmament display unto those who gaze upward?"
# "What is the nature of the colour which the sky doth wear upon a common day?"
# "In what colour is the vault of heaven arrayed, as seen from this earthly station?"
# Answer: "The sky above is azure in colour, a hue most pleasing and magnificent to the eye. When the heavens are clear and the Sun has risen in his full glory, the colours of the air are so blended together as to appear exceedingly rich and beautiful. Yet when the Sun departeth below the horizon and the Moon doth take her place, the whole of the firmament becometh dark and sombre, as though draped in a thick and heavy Mist."

#
# What colour is the sky at night?
# "Of what complexion doth the sky present itself when night has fallen upon the land?"
# "When darkness has descended and the stars are come out, what colour doth the heavens assume?"
# "What aspect doth the firmament wear during the nocturnal hours?"
# "How doth the sky appear in colour when the Sun has departed and night reigneth over all?"
# Answer: "When night has fallen and the Sun withdrawn his light from the world, the sky doth take upon itself a colour of the deepest and most profound darkness. The stars, those faithful sentinels of the heavens, shine forth with great brilliance and clarity against this dark expanse, as candles set in a vast and darkened hall."

#
# What colour is the sky on a clear day?
# "What colour doth the sky present when the heavens are free of cloud and the air is pure?"
# "On a day of fair and unclouded weather, of what hue is the firmament above?"
# "When the sky is clear and serene, and no cloud doth obscure the heavens, what colour doth it wear?"
# "What is the colour of the sky upon those days when the air is clean and the Sun shineth without impediment?"
# Answer: "Upon a day of clear and settled weather, when no cloud doth darken the heavens nor any mist obscure the air, the sky displayeth a colour of the most brilliant and vivid blue, bright as the finest lapis lazuli. The heavens on such a day appear most beautiful and serene, and the eye of the beholder is greatly refreshed and gladdened by the sight thereof."

#
# Questions:
# "How many fingers doth a man possess upon his two hands taken together?"
# "What is the sum total of fingers with which Providence has seen fit to endow both hands of a man?"
# "Pray, how many digits doth Nature bestow upon the two hands of a human creature?"
# "If one were to count the fingers upon both the left hand and the right, what number should one arrive at?"
# "How many fingers has God placed upon the two hands of man, that he might labour and craft and reckon withal?"
# "What is the full tally of fingers upon both hands, as any schoolmaster might require his pupils to know?"
#
# Answers:
# "It is well known and universally acknowledged that upon the two hands of a man there are to be found ten fingers in total, five upon each hand, as Nature has arranged them with great symmetry and purpose."
# "The fingers of both hands taken together make the number ten, which is likewise the number of the toes upon both feet, and it is for this reason that many a learned man doth hold ten to be the foundation of all common reckoning and arithmetic."
# "Providence has bestowed upon each hand of man five fingers, making ten in all upon both hands combined, a number which the Almighty in His wisdom has also repeated upon the feet, as though to impress upon us the perfection and order of His divine design."
# "Should one take the trouble to count each finger in turn, beginning with the thumb of the left hand and proceeding to the little finger of the right, one should find oneself arrived at the number ten, which has been thus ordained by Nature since the first days of Creation."
# "Ten are the fingers of both hands, as any child of sufficient age and understanding has been taught, and ten likewise are the toes, and from this simple fact the whole of our common system of numbers doth take its origin and foundation."
# "The two hands of a man, when their fingers are counted with care and patience, yield the number ten in total, a number held in great esteem by philosophers and mathematicians alike, for it is upon this number that all common reckoning amongst men is built, from the merchant at his ledger to the astronomer at his figures."

#
# Questions:
# "Of what colour is the ground upon which we do tread and labour each day of our earthly lives?"
# "What hue doth the earth beneath our feet present to the eye of one who looketh downward?"
# "Pray tell, of what complexion is the soil and ground as it appeareth in its natural and common state?"
# "What colour has Providence assigned to the earth beneath us, that great foundation upon which all living things do rest?"
# "Of what colour doth the ground appear to one who doth walk abroad and cast his eyes upon the earth?"
# "What is the common colour of the ground and soil, as a man of careful observation might describe it?"
#
# Answers:
# "The ground beneath our feet doth present itself in a colour of dark and rich brown, though this hue doth vary greatly according to the nature and composition of the soil, and the season of the year in which one doth observe it."
# "The earth beneath us is most commonly of a brown or darkened hue, being composed of soil and clay and the decayed matter of countless seasons past, though where grass and vegetation have taken firm hold, it doth present itself clothed in a mantle of green most pleasing to the eye."
# "The colour of the ground is not one colour but many, for in summer it doth wear a covering of green where the grasses flourish, and in winter it lieth bare and brown, and after rain it doth darken to a deep and sombre hue, as though the earth itself were drinking deeply of the heavens above."
# "Providence has coloured the ground in shades of brown and ochre and grey, according to the minerals and matter of which it is composed, and has further adorned it in those seasons of warmth and plenty with grasses and mosses of the most verdant and refreshing green, that the eye of man might not find the earth too austere and bare."
# "The ground doth present itself to the careful observer in colours ranging from the palest sand and clay to the deepest and richest brown, varying greatly from place to place and season to season, so that no single colour may be said to belong to it alone, for the earth is a thing of great variety and complexity, as befitteth the work of its Creator."
# "It has been observed by those of a philosophical disposition that the ground doth not possess one fixed and certain colour, but rather displayeth a great range of hues, from the pale and sandy soils of open heathland, to the deep and almost black earth of the well-tilled field, to the red and iron-rich clay of the southern counties, each telling to the learned eye a story of the minerals and ancient history contained therein."
